        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Should defaults be skipped with `-u NONE`? ... this might make tests (many of which use `-u NONE`) simpler\r\n\r\nIf tests want to nerf `_defaults.lua` they can do that in other ways, right? E.g. via the loader. It seems orthognal to `-u NONE`, and changing `-u NONE` to ignore random parts of startup seems very arbitrary. `_defaults.lua` happens to be written in Lua, but it is indeed part of `nvim` core and is no different than any other core feature.\r\n\r\nThis sounds like a general question about migrating tests, which is indeed a burden. But it's a tradeoff: in many cases we choose to migrate the tests, because we want to test real-world usage. But in some cases the churn is too high, so we adjust the test-runner.",
